"Tilmes S., Garcia R.R., Kinnison D.E., Gettelman A., Rasch P.J.","Impact of geoengineered aerosols on the troposphere and stratosphere",2009,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","114","12", D12305,"","",,,10.1029/2008JD011420,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-68849084155&partnerID=40&md5=ab7324277f8a1567dbe32637f1066cc5","Atmospheric Chemistry Division, National Center of Atmospheric Research, P.O. Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80307-3000, United States; Pacific Northwest National Laboratory, MSIN K9-34, 902 Battelle Boulevard, Richland, WA 99352, United States","Tilmes, S., Atmospheric Chemistry Division, National Center of Atmospheric Research, P.O. Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80307-3000, United States; Garcia, R.R., Atmospheric Chemistry Division, National Center of Atmospheric Research, P.O. Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80307-3000, United States; Kinnison, D.E., Atmospheric Chemistry Division, National Center of Atmospheric Research, P.O. Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80307-3000, United States; Gettelman, A., Atmospheric Chemistry Division, National Center of Atmospheric Research, P.O. Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80307-3000, United States; Rasch, P.J., Pacific Northwest National Laboratory, MSIN K9-34, 902 Battelle Boulevard, Richland, WA 99352, United States","A coupled chemistry climate model, the Whole Atmosphere Community Climate Model was used to perform a transient climate simulation to quantify the impact of geoengineered aerosols on atmospheric processes. In contrast to previous model studies, the impact on stratospheric chemistry, including heterogeneous chemistry in the polar regions, is considered in this simulation. In the geoengineering simulation, a constant stratospheric distribution of volcanic-sized, liquid sulfate aerosols is imposed in the period 2020-2050, corresponding to an injection of 2 Tg S/a. The aerosol cools the troposphere compared to a baseline simulation. Assuming an Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change AlB emission scenario, global warming is delayed by about 40 years in the troposphere with respect to the baseline scenario. Large local changes of precipitation and temperatures may occur as a result of geoengineering. Comparison with simulations carried out with the Community Atmosphere Model indicates the importance of stratospheric processes for estimating the impact of stratospheric aerosols on the Earth's climate. Changes in stratospheric dynamics and chemistry, especially faster heterogeneous reactions, reduce the recovery of the ozone layer in middle and high latitudes for the Southern Hemisphere. In the geoengineering case, the recovery of the Antarctic ozone hole is delayed by about 30 years on the basis of this model simulation. For the Northern Hemisphere, a onefold to twofold increase of the chemical ozone depletion occurs owing to a simulated stronger polar vortex and colder temperatures compared to the baseline simulation, in agreement with observational estimates. Copyright 2009 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric aerosols; Atmospheric chemistry; Atmospherics; Earth (planet); Global warming; Ozone; Ozone layer; Sulfur compounds; Troposphere; Upper atmosphere; Antarctic ozone hole; Atmospheric process; Chemical ozone depletion; Climate simulation; Community atmosphere model; Community climate models; Coupled chemistry-climate model; Earth's climate; Emission scenario; Geoengineering; Heterogeneous chemistry; Heterogeneous reactions; High Latitudes; Intergovernmental panel on climate changes; Model simulation; Model study; Northern Hemispheres; Polar Regions; Polar vortex; Southern Hemisphere; Stratospheric aerosols; Stratospheric chemistry; Sulfate aerosols; Simulators; aerosol; climate modeling; ozone depletion; polar region; precipitation (climatology); stratosphere; troposphere",,,,,,"Bodeker, G.E., Struthers, H., Connor, B.J., Dynamical containment of Antarctic ozone depletion (2002) Geophys. Res. Lett., 29 (1), p. 1098. , doi:10.1029/2001GL014206; Brasseur, G., 